(6, 'MC_006', '2025-08-26', 'Ordinance', 'Ordinance No. 2025-01: An Ordinance Mandating the Establishment of Community-Based Composting and Recycling Centers in All Barangays of Kaligayahan', 'aweaasdasdadsa', 'asdasda', 'Draft'),
(8, 'MC_008', '2025-08-26', 'Ordinance', 'An Ordinance Regulating the Use of Single-Use Plastic Bags by Commercial Establishments Within the City of Harmony', 'Section 1. Title and Purpose.\r\nThis ordinance shall be known as the \"Plastic Bag Reduction Ordinance.\" Its purpose is to promote the use of reusable bags and reduce the consumption of single-use plastic carryout bags in the City of Harmony.\r\n\r\nSection 2. Definitions.\r\nFor the purposes of this ordinance, the following terms shall be defined as:\r\n\r\n\"Commercial Establishment\" means any store, vendor, or business located within the City of Harmony that sells goods or provides services directly to the public. This includes, but is not limited to, grocery stores, convenience stores, and retail shops.\r\n\r\n\"Single-Use Plastic Bag\" means any bag made from plastic that is not designed or manufactured for multiple reuses. This definition does not include bags used for containing unwrapped produce, meat, or other food items, or bags for prescriptions.\r\n\r\n\"Reusable Bag\" means a bag with handles that is specifically designed and manufactured for multiple reuses and is made of cloth, durable plastic, or other similar durable material.\r\n\r\nSection 3. Regulation of Single-Use Plastic Bags.\r\nEffective 180 days after the adoption of this ordinance, no commercial establishment shall provide a single-use plastic bag to a customer at the point of sale.\r\n\r\nSection 4. Permitted Alternatives.\r\nCommercial establishments are encouraged to provide or sell reusable bags and may provide recyclable paper bags to customers.\r\n\r\nSection 5. Enforcement and Penalties.\r\n\r\nA commercial establishment found to be in violation of this ordinance shall be subject to a fine.\r\n\r\nThe first violation shall result in a written warning.\r\n\r\nA second violation within a 12-month period shall result in a fine of fifty dollars ($50.00).\r\n\r\nA third and each subsequent violation within a 12-month period shall result in a fine of one hundred dollars ($100.00).\r\n\r\nEnforcement of this ordinance shall be the responsibility of the City Manager\'s Office or a designated department.\r\n\r\nSection 6. Severability.\r\nIf any section, subsection, paragraph, sentence, or clause of this ordinance is for any reason held to be invalid or unconstitutional, such decision shall not affect the validity of the remaining portions of this ordinance.\r\n\r\nSection 7. Effective Date.\r\nThis ordinance shall take effect immediately upon its final passage and publication as required by law.\r\n\r\nKey Parts of an Ordinance\r\nAn ordinance is a law enacted by a local government body, such as a city council or county commission. It\'s different from a statute, which is a law passed by a state or national legislature. Here are the key components of a typical ordinance:\r\n\r\nTitle: A concise name that summarizes the ordinance\'s purpose.\r\n\r\nIntroducers: The names of the council members or legislative body members who are proposing the ordinance.\r\n\r\nPreamble (or \"Whereas\" clauses): The introductory section that explains the rationale and justification for the law. It sets the context and states the problem the ordinance aims to solve.\r\n\r\nBody (Sections): The main part of the ordinance, divided into sections for clarity.\r\n\r\nPurpose: A clear statement of the ordinance\'s goal.\r\n\r\nDefinitions: A glossary of terms to prevent confusion and ensure consistent interpretation.\r\n\r\nSubstantive Provisions: The core rules and regulations of the ordinance.\r\n\r\nEnforcement: Details on how the law will be enforced and what penalties will be applied for violations.\r\n\r\nSeverability Clause: A standard legal provision that ensures if one part of the law is found to be invalid, the rest of the law can remain in effect.\r\n\r\nEffective Date: Specifies when the ordinance will become active.', 'Councilwoman Anya Sharma and Councilman David Chen', 'Draft'),
(9, 'MC_009', '2025-08-27', 'Resolution', 'Resolution for Employee Recognition', 'Preamble\r\nWHEREAS, the success of our organization, [Organization Name], is built upon the dedication, hard work, and commitment of its employees; and\r\n\r\nWHEREAS, [Employee\'s Name] has consistently demonstrated exemplary performance, a positive attitude, and a strong commitment to the values and goals of [Organization Name]; and\r\n\r\nWHEREAS, [Employee\'s Name] has gone above and beyond their normal duties by [provide a specific example of their achievement, e.g., \"leading the successful launch of the new customer service initiative,\" or \"consistently mentoring junior staff members\"]; and\r\n\r\nWHEREAS, it is the policy and practice of this body to formally recognize and celebrate outstanding contributions that significantly benefit our workplace and community.\r\n\r\nResolution\r\nNOW, THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED that the [Governing Body, e.g., \"City Council,\" \"Board of Directors,\" \"Department Heads\"] of [Organization Name] hereby extends its deepest gratitude and commendation to [Employee\'s Name] for their exceptional service and dedication.\r\n\r\nBE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that a copy of this resolution be presented to [Employee\'s Name] as a token of our appreciation and that this resolution be recorded in the official minutes of this meeting.', 'Councilmember Maria Santiago', 'Draft'),
(10, 'MC_010', '2025-08-27', 'Resolution', 'Resolution Honoring a Retiring Board Member', 'Preamble\r\nWHEREAS, the Board of Directors of [Organization Name] recognizes the invaluable service and commitment of [Board Member\'s Name], who has served with distinction as a member of this Board since [Year of Start]; and\r\n\r\nWHEREAS, [Board Member\'s Name] has provided wise counsel and dedicated leadership during their tenure, playing a critical role in [mention a specific achievement, e.g., \"guiding our organization through a period of significant growth,\" \"overseeing the successful completion of the community center project,\" or \"establishing the annual scholarship fund\"]; and\r\n\r\nWHEREAS, their integrity, passion, and tireless efforts have left a lasting positive impact on our organization and the community we serve; and\r\n\r\nWHEREAS, it is the desire of this Board to formally recognize and express its profound gratitude to [Board Member\'s Name] upon their retirement.\r\n\r\nResolution\r\nNOW, THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED that the Board of Directors of [Organization Name] extends its sincere appreciation to [Board Member\'s Name] for their exemplary service and profound contributions.\r\n\r\nBE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that this resolution be adopted, entered into the official records of the Board, and a copy be presented to [Board Member\'s Name] as a small token of our great respect and gratitude.', 'Board President Sarah Chen', 'Draft'),
(11, 'MC_011', '2025-08-27', 'Ordinance', 'Ordinance Establishing a Community Garden Program', 'Preamble\r\nWHEREAS, a community-led initiative has identified a desire among residents for access to local gardening spaces; and\r\n\r\nWHEREAS, the promotion of healthy living, sustainable practices, and community engagement are vital goals for the city of [City Name]; and\r\n\r\nWHEREAS, the establishment of a public community garden provides an opportunity for residents to grow their own food, connect with their neighbors, and beautify underutilized public spaces; and\r\n\r\nWHEREAS, the City Council has identified [Address or Name of Location, e.g., \"the vacant lot at 123 Main Street\"] as a suitable location for the pilot program; and\r\n\r\nWHEREAS, it is the intent of the City Council to establish clear rules and regulations to ensure the safe and equitable operation of the community garden.\r\n\r\nOrdinance\r\nNOW, THEREFORE, BE IT ORDAINED by the City Council of [City Name] as follows:\r\n\r\nSection 1: Establishment. There is hereby established the [City Name] Community Garden Program to be overseen by the [Governing Department, e.g., \"Parks and Recreation Department\"]. The initial site for the program shall be located at [Address or Name of Location].\r\n\r\nSection 2: Purpose. The purpose of this ordinance is to promote urban agriculture, provide educational opportunities, and foster community spirit through the management of shared garden spaces.\r\n\r\nSection 3: Administration and Fees. The [Governing Department] shall be responsible for the administration and oversight of the program, including but not limited to the allocation of plots, development of a waiting list, and enforcement of rules. The Department is authorized to charge a reasonable annual fee for garden plots to cover administrative costs and maintenance.\r\n\r\nSection 4: Rules and Regulations. All participants in the Community Garden Program shall adhere to the rules and regulations established by the [Governing Department]. These rules shall include provisions for garden plot maintenance, proper waste disposal, prohibited plantings, and conflict resolution.\r\n\r\nSection 5: Severability. Should any part of this ordinance be deemed invalid by a court of competent jurisdiction, the remaining sections shall remain in full force and effect.\r\n\r\nSection 6: Effective Date. This ordinance shall become effective upon its final passage and publication in accordance with law.', 'Councilmember Maria Santiago', 'Draft'),
(13, 'MC_013', '2025-08-29', 'Ordinance', 'An Ordinance Banning The Use Of Single-Use Plastic Bags In All Commercial Establishments', 'Section 1. Title. This ordinance shall be known as the \"Single-Use Plastic Bag Reduction Ordinance of 2025.\"\r\n\r\nSection 2. Declaration of Policy. It is the policy of the local government to protect and preserve the environment, promote public health, and encourage sustainable practices. The proliferation of single-use plastic bags contributes significantly to environmental pollution, drainage system clogging, and harm to wildlife. Therefore, this ordinance aims to regulate and eventually eliminate the use of single-use plastic bags within the city.\r\n\r\nSection 3. Definition of Terms. For purposes of this ordinance, the following terms are defined as:\r\n\r\nSingle-use plastic bags: Any bag made of plastic, intended for one-time use, and provided by a commercial establishment to a customer for carrying goods. This does not include reusable bags, or plastic bags used to contain unwrapped food items like fruits, vegetables, meat, or fish.\r\n\r\nCommercial establishment: Any business, including but not limited to grocery stores, supermarkets, convenience stores, and retail shops, that provides goods or services to the public.\r\n\r\nReusable bag: A bag with handles that is specifically designed and manufactured for multiple uses and is made of cloth, durable plastic, or other non-disposable materials.\r\n\r\nSection 4. Prohibited Acts.\r\n\r\nNo commercial establishment shall provide single-use plastic bags to customers at the point of sale.\r\n\r\nCustomers are prohibited from using single-use plastic bags for carrying goods purchased from commercial establishments within the city limits.\r\n\r\nSection 5. Alternatives and Incentives.\r\n\r\nCommercial establishments are encouraged to provide alternative, reusable bags for sale or offer them for free at their discretion.\r\n\r\nA \"bring your own bag\" campaign will be launched by the local government to encourage residents to use reusable bags.\r\n\r\nThe local government will explore partnerships with environmental organizations to conduct educational campaigns on the proper disposal and recycling of plastics.\r\n\r\nSection 6. Penalties.\r\n\r\nAny violation of this ordinance shall be subject to the following penalties:\r\n\r\nFirst Offense: A fine of P1,000.\r\n\r\nSecond Offense: A fine of P3,000 and the suspension of the business permit for one week.\r\n\r\nThird and Subsequent Offenses: A fine of P5,000 and the revocation of the business permit.\r\n\r\nSection 7. Separability Clause. If any part of this ordinance is declared unconstitutional or invalid, the other parts not affected shall remain in full force and effect.\r\n\r\nSection 8. Effectivity. This ordinance shall take effect fifteen (15) days after its publication in a newspaper of general circulation.', 'Councilor Maria Santos and Councilor Jose Reyes', 'Draft'),
(14, 'MC_014', '2025-08-29', 'Ordinance', 'An Ordinance Banning The Use Of Single-Use Plastic Bags In All Commercial Establishments', 'Section 1. Title. This ordinance shall be known as the \"Single-Use Plastic Bag Reduction Ordinance of 2025.\"\r\n\r\nSection 2. Declaration of Policy. It is the policy of the local government to protect and preserve the environment, promote public health, and encourage sustainable practices. The proliferation of single-use plastic bags contributes significantly to environmental pollution, drainage system clogging, and harm to wildlife. Therefore, this ordinance aims to regulate and eventually eliminate the use of single-use plastic bags within the city.\r\n\r\nSection 3. Definition of Terms. For purposes of this ordinance, the following terms are defined as:\r\n\r\nSingle-use plastic bags: Any bag made of plastic, intended for one-time use, and provided by a commercial establishment to a customer for carrying goods. This does not include reusable bags, or plastic bags used to contain unwrapped food items like fruits, vegetables, meat, or fish.\r\n\r\nCommercial establishment: Any business, including but not limited to grocery stores, supermarkets, convenience stores, and retail shops, that provides goods or services to the public.\r\n\r\nReusable bag: A bag with handles that is specifically designed and manufactured for multiple uses and is made of cloth, durable plastic, or other non-disposable materials.\r\n\r\nSection 4. Prohibited Acts.\r\n\r\nNo commercial establishment shall provide single-use plastic bags to customers at the point of sale.\r\n\r\nCustomers are prohibited from using single-use plastic bags for carrying goods purchased from commercial establishments within the city limits.\r\n\r\nSection 5. Alternatives and Incentives.\r\n\r\nCommercial establishments are encouraged to provide alternative, reusable bags for sale or offer them for free at their discretion.\r\n\r\nA \"bring your own bag\" campaign will be launched by the local government to encourage residents to use reusable bags.\r\n\r\nThe local government will explore partnerships with environmental organizations to conduct educational campaigns on the proper disposal and recycling of plastics.\r\n\r\nSection 6. Penalties.\r\n\r\nAny violation of this ordinance shall be subject to the following penalties:\r\n\r\nFirst Offense: A fine of P1,000.\r\n\r\nSecond Offense: A fine of P3,000 and the suspension of the business permit for one week.\r\n\r\nThird and Subsequent Offenses: A fine of P5,000 and the revocation of the business permit.\r\n\r\nSection 7. Separability Clause. If any part of this ordinance is declared unconstitutional or invalid, the other parts not affected shall remain in full force and effect.\r\n\r\nSection 8. Effectivity. This ordinance shall take effect fifteen (15) days after its publication in a newspaper of general circulation.', 'Councilor Maria Santos and Councilor Jose Reyes', 'Draft'),
(15, 'MC_015', '2025-08-30', 'Ordinance', 'City Ordinance No. 2025-01: An Ordinance Regulating the Use of Single-Use Plastic Bags and Promoting the Use of Reusable Bags within City Limits', 'This ordinance prohibits all commercial establishments, including grocery stores, retail shops, and markets, from providing single-use plastic bags to customers. It requires these establishments to offer reusable bags for sale or to encourage customers to bring their own. The ordinance also outlines a schedule of penalties for non-compliance, starting with a warning for the first offense and escalating to fines for subsequent violations. The goal is to reduce plastic waste and promote environmental sustainability.', 'Councilor Maria Reyes', 'Draft'),
(16, 'MC_016', '2025-08-30', 'Ordinance', 'City Ordinance No. 2025-02: The Smoke-Free Public Spaces Act of 2025', 'This ordinance establishes all public parks, government buildings, and designated public transport stops as smoke-free zones. It prohibits smoking, including the use of e-cigarettes and vapes, in these areas. The ordinance includes a provision for designated smoking areas in specific, non-public locations, as determined by the City Health Department. Violators are subject to fines, and a portion of the collected fines is allocated to public health awareness campaigns.', 'Councilor David Chen and Councilor Aisha Khan', 'Draft'),
(17, 'MC_017', '2025-08-30', 'Ordinance', 'City Ordinance No. 2025-03: An Ordinance Amending the City’s Comprehensive Zoning Plan to Include Regulations for Short-Term Rentals', 'This ordinance amends the city\'s existing zoning plan to regulate the operation of short-term rentals (e.g., Airbnb, Vrbo) in residential areas. It mandates that all short-term rental properties must be registered with the city and requires property owners to obtain a special permit. The ordinance limits the number of days a property can be rented out per year and establishes rules regarding noise levels and parking. It also sets up a system for receiving and investigating complaints from neighbors to maintain the residential character of neighborhoods.', 'Mayor Ben Miller', 'Draft'),
(18, 'MC_018', '2025-08-30', 'Ordinance', 'City Ordinance No. 2025-04: The Youth Protection Curfew Act', 'This ordinance establishes a city-wide curfew for minors under the age of 18. It prohibits them from being in public places or on the streets between 10:00 PM and 5:00 AM on weekdays and 11:00 PM and 5:00 AM on weekends, unless accompanied by a parent or legal guardian. The ordinance provides exceptions for minors traveling to or from work, school-sanctioned events, or in case of an emergency. The goal is to enhance public safety and protect minors from potential dangers.', 'The City Council Committee on Youth and Family', 'Draft'),
(19, 'MC_019', '2025-08-30', 'Ordinance', 'City Ordinance No. 2025-05: An Ordinance Regulating Responsible Pet Ownership and Animal Control', 'This ordinance requires all dogs and cats within city limits to be registered annually with the City Animal Services Department and to be microchipped. It mandates that pet owners clean up after their pets in public spaces and keep them on a leash in parks and on sidewalks. The ordinance also includes provisions for the humane treatment of animals, setting penalties for animal cruelty and neglect. It establishes a protocol for the impoundment of stray animals and their subsequent adoption or humane euthanasia.', 'Councilor Sarah Lee', 'Draft'),
(20, 'MC_020', '2025-08-30', 'Resolution', 'City Resolution No. 2025-R1: A Resolution Expressing the City Council’s Strong Support for the Local Farmers’ Market', 'This resolution is a formal statement of the city council\'s support for the weekly farmers\' market. It acknowledges the market\'s role in promoting local agriculture, providing healthy food options, and fostering community engagement. The resolution does not create a law or allocate funds, but it serves as an official endorsement from the city government, which can be used to attract more vendors, customers, and potential grants.', 'Councilor David Chen', 'Draft'),
(21, 'MC_021', '2025-08-30', 'Resolution', 'City Resolution No. 2025-R2: A Resolution Authorizing the City Manager to Enter into a Contract for the Downtown Beautification Project', 'This resolution authorizes the city manager to negotiate and sign a contract with a specific landscaping company for the beautification of the downtown area. It outlines the scope of the project, including the installation of new planters, benches, and decorative lighting. This resolution is a one-time administrative action that grants the city manager the authority to proceed with the project without the need for a new ordinance.', 'Councilor Ben Miller', 'Draft'),
(22, 'MC_022', '2025-08-30', 'Resolution', 'City Resolution No. 2025-R3: A Resolution Declaring October as \"Community Arts and Culture Month\"', 'This resolution formally declares the month of October as Community Arts and Culture Month in the city. It is a symbolic act that encourages residents to participate in local art exhibits, performances, and cultural events. This resolution does not create a law but is used to raise awareness and officially recognize the importance of arts and culture in the community.', 'Mayor Anya Sharma', 'Draft'),
(23, 'MC_023', '2025-08-30', 'Resolution', 'City Resolution No. 2025-R4: A Resolution Creating a Special Task Force to Address Homelessness', 'This resolution establishes a temporary, ad-hoc Homelessness Task Force composed of city officials, community leaders, and non-profit representatives. The resolution defines the task force\'s purpose, which is to study the root causes of homelessness in the city and to present a set of policy recommendations to the city council within a specified timeframe (e.g., six months). Once the recommendations are submitted, the task force\'s mission is complete, and it is dissolved.', 'The City Council', 'Draft'),
(24, 'MC_024', '2025-08-30', 'Resolution', 'City Resolution No. 2025-R5: A Resolution Amending the Fiscal Year 2025 Budget to Allocate Funds for Emergency Road Repairs', 'This resolution authorizes the transfer of a specific amount of money from the city\'s contingency fund to the Public Works Department to cover the unexpected costs of repairing roads damaged by a recent storm. This is a specific, one-time action that amends the budget for a particular purpose and does not create a permanent change to the city\'s financial policy.', 'The City Council Committee on Finance', 'Draft'),
(25, 'MC_025', '2025-09-01', 'Ordinance', 'City Ordinance No. 2025-05: An Ordinance Requiring All Public and Commercial Establishments to Install and Maintain Proper Waste Segregation Bins', 'Section 1. Short Title. This Ordinance shall be known as the \"Waste Segregation Ordinance of 2025.\"\r\n\r\nSection 2. Declaration of Policy. It is the policy of the city to protect and advance the right of the people to a balanced and healthful ecology in accordance with the rhythm and harmony of nature. This ordinance supports the principles of the Ecological Solid Waste Management Act of 2000 (Republic Act No. 9003) by implementing a localized system of waste segregation.\r\n\r\nSection 3. Scope and Coverage. This ordinance shall apply to all public and commercial establishments, including but not limited to:\r\n\r\nRestaurants, cafes, and food courts\r\n\r\nShopping malls, supermarkets, and retail stores\r\n\r\nHotels, resorts, and lodging facilities\r\n\r\nSchools, universities, and other educational institutions\r\n\r\nHospitals, clinics, and other medical facilities\r\n\r\nGovernment offices and public markets\r\n\r\nSection 4. Waste Segregation Requirements. All establishments covered by this ordinance are required to provide and maintain clearly labeled waste bins for at least three types of waste:\r\n\r\nBiodegradable (e.g., food scraps, plant-based materials)\r\n\r\nNon-Biodegradable/Recyclable (e.g., paper, cardboard, plastic bottles, glass)\r\n\r\nResidual (e.g., soiled materials, broken ceramics, wrappers that cannot be recycled)\r\n\r\nThe bins must be strategically placed in accessible areas to encourage compliance from customers and staff.\r\n\r\nSection 5. Penalties. Any establishment found in violation of this ordinance shall be subject to the following penalties:\r\n\r\nFirst Offense: A fine of ₱2,500 and a written warning.\r\n\r\nSecond Offense: A fine of ₱5,000 and a mandatory attendance at a waste management seminar.\r\n\r\nThird Offense: A fine of ₱10,000 and suspension of the business permit for thirty (30) days.\r\n\r\nSection 6. Repealing Clause. All ordinances, resolutions, and parts thereof which are inconsistent with the provisions of this Ordinance are hereby repealed or modified accordingly.\r\n\r\nSection 7. Separability Clause. If any provision or part of this Ordinance is declared unconstitutional or invalid, the other parts or provisions not affected thereby shall remain in full force and effect.\r\n\r\nSection 8. Effectivity. This Ordinance shall take effect fifteen (15) days after its publication in a newspaper of local circulation.', 'Councilor Maria Santos', 'Draft'),
